ee of using the perks to build out his own business while shortchanging Mid=
dleton on producer fees and credits. Lee volleyed back, painting Middleton =
as a dilettante more interested in high-rolling than rolling up his sleeves=
 and working, suggesting it was Middleton who bailed financially after thei=
r partnership collapsed under the weight of a fresh
venture with Casey Affleck.

=C2=A0

As the legal battle unfolded, the media devoured the scandalous details:=C2=
=A0 Middleton=E2=80=99s debauched escapades with Leonardo DiCaprio and frie=
nds, including the =E2=80=9Cblack-out drunk=E2=80=9D rich boy stumbling thr=
ough a glass door on a yacht, crying, and urinating in his pants in front o=
f Lee=E2=80=99s business contacts; his alleged use of a security firm to ta=
il a
girlfriend who happens to be the daughter of New Hampshire Senator Jeanne S=
haheen; and his donations to Donald Trump=E2=80=99s 2016 campaign. The Holl=
ywood Reporter covered ( https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/business/busines=
s-news/allegations-prostitution-more-hollywoods-nastiest-producer-feud-1299=
878/?utm_campaign=3DWhat+I%27m+Hearing%2B+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F28%2F25%29&u=
tm_content=3DWhat+I%27m+Hearing%2B+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F28%2F25%29&utm_medi=
um=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) =
the story in 2020 (I worked there at the time, but wasn=E2=80=99t involved =
in the article),
leading to a defamation lawsuit by Middleton against THR for portraying him=
 as a drunk. Covering all his bases, Middleton also sued his sobriety coach=
es for overbilling him and supplying him with booze. (The lawsuit against T=
HR eventually fizzled.)

=C2=A0

As with most scandals, the furor eventually dimmed, and the legal tussle be=
